4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT REVISING SPEED LIMIT LAWS; INCREASING DAYTIME AND
5 NIGHTTIME SPEED LIMITS ON NATIONAL HIGHWAYS THAT HAVE BEEN EXPANDED TO FOUR LANES,
6 EXCEPT IN SPECIAL SPEED ZONES; AND AMENDING SECTIONS 61-8-303 AND 61-8-725, MCA.”
7
8 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
9
10 Section 1. Section 61-8-303, MCA, is amended to read:
11 "61-8-303. Speed restrictions. (1) Except as provided in 61-8-309, 61-8-310, and 61-8-312, the
12 speed limit for vehicles traveling:
13 (a) on an interstate highway outside an urbanized area of 50,000 population or more is 80 miles an
14 hour at all times and the speed limit for vehicles traveling on interstate highways within an urbanized area of
15 50,000 population or more is 65 miles an hour at all times;
16 (b) on any portion of a national highway that has been expanded to four lanes and that is at least
17 15 miles long is 75 miles an hour during the daytime and 70 miles an hour during the nighttime, unless the area
18 is a special speed zone;
19 (c) on any other public highway of this state is 70 miles an hour during the daytime and 65 miles
20 an hour during the nighttime;
21 (d) in an urban district is 25 miles an hour.
22 (2) A vehicle subject to the speed limits imposed in subsection (1) may exceed the speed limits
23 imposed in subsection (1) by 10 miles an hour in order to overtake and pass a vehicle and return safely to the
24 right-hand lane under the following circumstances:
25 (a) while traveling on a two-lane road; and
26 (b) in a designated passing zone.
27 (3) Subject to the maximum speed limits set forth in subsection (1), a person shall operate a
28 vehicle in a careful and prudent manner and at a reduced rate of speed no greater than is reasonable and
